   <titles>
      <title>Diagonalizable Matrices</title>
      <plain.title>Diagonalizable Matrices</plain.title>
   </titles>
   <intro>
      <block>
         <block.body>
            <para>
               <para.body>Here we consider the situation where a given <math>
                     <latex>(n,n)</latex>
                  </math>-matrix <math>
                     <latex>\Mtrx{A}</latex>
                  </math> has a basis <math>
                     <latex>\EuScript{B}</latex>
                  </math> of eigenvectors for <math>
                     <latex>\RNr[n]</latex>
                  </math>. This happens if each eigenvalue <math>
                     <latex>\lambda</latex>
                  </math> has algebraic multiplicity equal to the dimension of its eigenspace. Changing from standard coordinates to <math>
                     <latex>\EuScript{B}</latex>
                  </math>-coordinates, results in a diagonal matrix <math>
                     <latex>\Mtrx{D}</latex>
                  </math> with</para.body>
            </para>
            <math.array column="3">
               <row rowspan="1">
                  <cell colspan="2" halign="center" valign="middle">
                     <math>
                        <latex>\Mtrx{D}</latex>
                     </math>
                  </cell>
                  <cell colspan="1" halign="center" valign="middle">
                     <text>=</text>
                  </cell>
                  <cell colspan="2" halign="center" valign="middle">
                     <math>
                        <latex>\Mtrx{C}_{\EuScript{B}\EuScript{S}} \Mtrx{A} \Mtrx{C}_{\EuScript{S}\EuScript{B}}</latex>
                     </math>
                  </cell>
               </row>
            </math.array>
            <para>
               <para.body>Therefore we call such a matrix <math>
                     <latex>\Mtrx{A}</latex>
                  </math> diagonalizable.</para.body>
            </para>
         </block.body>
      </block>
   </intro>
